Analysing ESG report using Natural Language Processing¶

Summary¶

Environment, Social and Corporate Governance (ESG) refers to the three central factors in measuring the sustainability and societal impact of an investment in a company or business. These criteria help to better determin the future financial performance of companies (return and risk).

This analysis extracts text from a ESG report in PDF format from the internet, performs NLP on these information, summaries the key ESG initiatives with WordClouds, TDIDFs and discovers topics by building a Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA) model.

Given that ESG is a broad topic. Different companies focus on different aspects of ESG depending on their business operations and culture. One can potentially ingest more ESG reports from different companies across all sectors and industries to capture relevant ESG topics. This to be attempted in another analysis.

Create Folders

In [8]:
import sys
import os
import shutil
DATA_FOLDER = '\\COMPDrive\credit\20075503d\COMProfile\Desktop\data'
def CreateFolder(in_dir):
    print('创建'+in_dir+'文件夹')
    isExists=os.path.exists(in_dir)
    if not isExists: #不存在则创建
        print('创建'+in_dir+'文件夹成功')
    else:
        print(in_dir+'文件夹已存在')
CreateFolder(DATA_FOLDER)

Text Extraction¶

Extract information from the PDF report. This process may take some time. Do be patient.

You may skip to the last step of this section if you have previously extracted the contents and stored in a json file.

In [19]:
def extract_pdf(file, verbose=False):
    
    if verbose:
        print('Processing {}'.format(file))

    try:
        resource_manager = PDFResourceManager()
        fake_file_handle = io.StringIO()
        codec = 'utf-8'
        laparams = LAParams()

        converter = TextConverter(resource_manager, fake_file_handle, codec=codec, laparams=laparams)
        page_interpreter = PDFPageInterpreter(resource_manager, converter)
        
        password = ""
        maxpages = 0
        caching = True
        pagenos = set()

        content = []

        for page in PDFPage.get_pages(file,
                                      pagenos, 
                                      maxpages=maxpages,
                                      password=password,
                                      caching=True,
                                      check_extractable=False):

            page_interpreter.process_page(page)

            content.append(fake_file_handle.getvalue())

            fake_file_handle.truncate(0)
            fake_file_handle.seek(0)        

        text = '##PAGE_BREAK##'.join(content)

        # close open handles
        converter.close()
        fake_file_handle.close()
        
        return text

    except Exception as e:
        print(e)

        # close open handles
        converter.close()
        fake_file_handle.close()

        return ""
In [20]:
def extract_content(url):
    """
    A simple user define function that, given a url, download PDF text content
    Parse PDF and return plain text version
    """
    headers={"User-Agent":"Mozilla/5.0"}

    try:
        # retrieve PDF binary stream
        r = requests.get(url, allow_redirects=True, headers=headers)
        
        # access pdf content
        text = extract_pdf(io.BytesIO(r.content))

        # return concatenated content
        return text

    except:
        return ""

Peck, President and CEO, U.S.VETS, USMC ’68 – ‘71\n\nIn Action\nMAKE CAMO YOUR CAUSE\n\nINTRODUCTION\nABOUT FOX \nOUR APPROACH \nFISCAL YEAR 2022 HIGHLIGHTS\n\nCOMMUNITY FORWARD\nGiving For Good\nFOX Forward\nGiving Across the Company\n\nPEOPLE FORWARD\nSUSTAINABLY FORWARD\nPOLICY FORWARD\nDATA FORWARD\nSASB APPENDIX\n\nFOX partnered with U.S.VETS for their “Make Camo Your Cause”  \ncampaign to #HONORUSVETS. The cause marketing campaign, \nlaunched in November of 2021, brings visibility to the organization’s \nmission to further establish camouflage as the official symbol of  \nveteran support. FOX activated widespread support across our  \nnetworks and businesses in support of the campaign and the  \norganization’s goal to end homelessness for those who have served.\n\nFOX Sports featured on-air coverage of the campaign throughout \nthe week of Veterans Day, including airing U.S.VETS public service \nannouncements across FS1 and FS2, totaling nearly 30 minutes of \nairtime. FOX Sports, FS1, FS2 and FOX Deportes logos all went camo \nfor the day. The campaign viewership reached nearly 12 million.\n\nFOX News featured coverage of “Make Camo Your Cause” during  \nFOX & Friends and FOX News Primetime. Our FOX anchors showed  \noff their camo on-air and on their social channels. FOX News social  \nchannels were also themed with camo to spread the important  \nmessage. \n\n12\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##UNITED STATES VETERANS INITIATIVE\nFOX established and continues to nurture a \nstrong partnership with the United States \nVeterans Initiative (U.S.VETS), a national \nleader in providing housing, employment \nand mental health services to veterans \nacross the country. Through food services, \nsite improvements and supply drives, FOX is \ncommitted to giving veterans the opportunity \nto live with dignity and independence.\n\nFOX Forward funded meals for more than 600 \nveteran residents in four U.S.VETS residential \nfacilities in recognition of Memorial Day.\n\nINTRODUCTION\nABOUT FOX \nOUR APPROACH \nFISCAL YEAR 2022 HIGHLIGHTS\n\nCOMMUNITY FORWARD\nGiving For Good\nFOX Forward\nGiving Across the Company\n\nPEOPLE FORWARD\nSUSTAINABLY FORWARD\nPOLICY FORWARD\nDATA FORWARD\nSASB APPENDIX\n\nFOX Entertainment utilized a Times Square billboard in New York  \nCity to display the #HONORUSVETS messaging, reaching scores of \npeople throughout Veterans Day. American Red Cross disaster workers \nfrom all over the country helped and continue to assist the people  \nof Kentucky, Tennessee, Arkansas and Missouri, focused on providing \nshelter, meals and comfort. Fox Corporation contributed $1 million  \nto their efforts and double matched employee donations.  \nOver 1,500 families received funds to begin to rebuild their lives,  \nincluding replacing furniture, securing new housing and purchasing \nother necessities. Across FOX networks, stations and platforms, we \nhighlighted the important relief efforts by the Red Cross, supplemented \nby interviews and viewer calls to action to support the cause.\n\nUKRAINE CRISIS RELIEF EFFORTS \nFOX donated $1 million to the American Red Cross to provide aid and \nresources including water, medical supplies, housing support and \nmore to the most vulnerable both within Ukraine and for those forced \nto leave their homes. The Company double matched employee  \ndonations to American Red Cross Ukraine relief efforts through FOX \nGiving. FOX also featured several Ukraine segments with Red Cross \nrepresentatives to discuss the humanitarian aid and mental health \nsupport being provided to those affected by the crisis in Ukraine.\n\n“As a forward-thinking  \nAnnual Disaster Giving \nProgram member,  \nFOX ensures our  \norganization is ready  \nto help people and  \ncommunities prepare \nfor the unexpected  \nand provide comfort  \nto families at  \na moment’s notice.  \nThis past year, FOX and its  \ngenerous viewers  \nresponded in extraordinary  \nways.”\n\n- Gail McGovern, President and CEO,  \nAmerican Red Cross\n\nINTRODUCTION\nABOUT FOX \nOUR APPROACH \nFISCAL YEAR 2022 HIGHLIGHTS\n\nCOMMUNITY FORWARD\nGiving For Good\nFOX Forward\nGiving Across the Company\n\nPEOPLE FORWARD\nSUSTAINABLY FORWARD\nPOLICY FORWARD\nDATA FORWARD\nSASB APPENDIX\n\n14\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##FOX VIEWER SUPPORT \nOur campaign to support Red Cross efforts was amplified by  \nthe extraordinary generosity of FOX viewers through their donations  \nto our FOX Forward fundraising microsite. Following calls to action \nfrom FOX & Friends, multiple FOX TV stations, FOX Sports and  \nFOX Entertainment platforms, the microsite received more than  \n$365,000 in donations to support the response and recovery efforts  \nsurrounding the tornadoes in the South and Midwest.\n\nThe generosity of FOX viewers, across all our platforms, shone \nthrough with contributions to the FOX Red Cross Ukraine relief effort \nmicrosite surpassing $13 million.\n\nRED CROSS “GIVING DAY” \nFurther attention was brought to the essential work of the Red Cross \nthrough an on-air and social media push during Red Cross Month  \n“Giving Day” on March 23. FOX Weather meteorologists recorded \nawareness messages that ran the week leading up to Giving Day.  \nOn Giving Day, in-studio and virtual interviews were featured as well \nas a remote segment from a Red Cross-supported Los Angeles blood \ndonation center.\n\nFOX Weather meteorologists boosted the program across its platform, \nleading to $54,000 in donations from FOX viewers, adding to the over-\nall total of $4 million to the campaign. \n\nINTRODUCTION\nABOUT FOX \nOUR APPROACH \nFISCAL YEAR 2022 HIGHLIGHTS\n\nCOMMUNITY FORWARD\nGiving For Good\nFOX Forward\nGiving Across the Company\n\nPEOPLE FORWARD\nSUSTAINABLY FORWARD\nPOLICY FORWARD\nDATA FORWARD\nSASB APPENDIX\n\n15\n\nAMERICAN RED CROSS\nFOX continues its pledge to pre-invest in national disaster relief through \nour American Red Cross Annual Disaster Giving Program (ADGP)  \npartnership. Our annual gift supports relief efforts in response to disasters \nacross the nation, providing safe shelter, hot meals, emotional support  \nand resources to aid in recovery.\n\nThe ADGP funds the Red Cross response efforts to more than 60,000  \ndisasters of all sizes each year across the nation, helping families and  \ncommunities become better prepared and more resilient ahead of the next \ncrisis. Vital systems and supplies must be in place before disaster strikes, \nand FOX’s dedication and critical investments ensure that the tens of  \nthousands of Red Cross workers are fully ready to turn heartbreak into hope.\n\nThose struggling after a disaster turn to the Red Cross because they know \nthey will get the support they need to begin to rebuild their lives. The Red \nCross is dedicated to engaging local communities, evidenced by the fact \nthat 90% of Red Cross workers are volunteers. FOX’s participation in the \nADGP allows volunteers to be fully trained to jump into action to help those \nstruggling in their own neighborhoods.\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##•  Westwood Charter Elementary \n\nSchool, whose art instructor \nteaches oil pastels, watercolor, \ndrawing and other creative arts  \non an age-appropriate basis to  \neach grade\n\n•  Emerson Community Charter \n\nMiddle School, which launched an \nArts & Media Academy that features \nclasses on video production, \ncostume design and scriptwriting\n\n•  Van Nuys High School, which has a \nPerforming Arts Magnet program \nthat offers classes in dance, theater, \nmusic and film\n\n•  54th Street Elementary School, \nwhich works with the Why Can’t \nWe Make A Difference Foundation \nto provide students with classes \nin drama, choir and visual arts\n\n•  Crenshaw Magnet High School, \n\nwhich includes a Visual and \nPerforming Arts Pathway with \nclasses in visual arts, dance, \nmusic, digital art and media\n\n•  Canfield Elementary School, \n\nwhich offers students programs \nin visual arts, dance and music\n\nIn Action\nFOX FOR STUDENTS\n\nIn the summer of 2021, FOX debuted its “FOX For Students” program, \na broad and deep investment in local schools across Los Angeles.  \nThe program provides 12 local schools with the resources needed  \nfor activities that ignite students’ passion in the arts, creativity and \nstorytelling.\n\nIn its first year, the program helped to provide costumes and set \nsupplies for Emerson Middle School’s drama program, LCD televisions \nfor Palms Middle School’s Modern Media and Communications Magnet \nprogram and performance equipment for 54th Street Elementary \nSchool, including microphones, speakers and computers. \n\nIn addition to these arts and education opportunities, we recognize \nthe importance of daily healthy food to enable students to thrive and \nsucceed in and outside of the classroom. FOX partnered again with the \nLos Angeles Regional Food Bank’s BackPack Program to provide fresh \nfood all school year long to two schools in the Los Angeles Unified and \nCompton Unified School Districts.\n\nFOX supports recreational programs to serve youth across the country, \nincluding students in our FOX Studio Lot neighborhood. Through a \nspecial grant to Cheviot Hills Pony Baseball Association, students \nwere able to make a special trip to the Baseball Hall of Fame, and we \nprovided the Cheviot Hills Recreation Center summer campers with \nFOX backpacks, cooling towels and water bottles.\n\nEMPOWERING STUDENTS IN  \nOUR LOCAL COMMUNITIES\n\n•  Palms Middle School, which \nhas a new Modern Media and \nCommunications Magnet program \nfocused on career and technical \neducation for the communications-\nbased jobs of the 21st century, with  \na curriculum designed around \nwriting, public speaking, technology \nand film & video\n\n•  School for the Visual Arts and \n\nHumanities, where high school \nstudents focus on career and \ntechnical education in either \nanimation or fine art\n\n•  Samuel Gompers Middle School, \n\nwhich has a STEAM Magnet \nprogram offering classes in drama, \nmusic, coding, robotics and digital \nproduction\n\n•  Hamilton High School, which \n\nhas a new film program focused \non technical education in video \nproduction, screenwriting, music \ntechnology and broadcast journalism\n\n•  Overland Elementary School, which \n\nlaunched a visual arts program for \nstudents in Fall 2021\n\n•  Castle Heights Elementary School, \n\nwhose art teacher introduces \nstudents to the work of famous artists \nand teaches lessons based on the \nstyle of those artists\n\nINTRODUCTION\nABOUT FOX \nOUR APPROACH \nFISCAL YEAR 2022 HIGHLIGHTS\n\nCOMMUNITY FORWARD\nGiving For Good\nFOX Forward\nGiving Across the Company\n\nPEOPLE FORWARD\nSUSTAINABLY FORWARD\nPOLICY FORWARD\nDATA FORWARD\nSASB APPENDIX\n\n16\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##COLLEGE TO CONGRESS \nFor the past three years, Fox Corporation has \nparticipated in the College to Congress (C2C) internship \nprogram that creates a pathway for economically \ndisadvantaged students to work in the halls of Congress \nby providing financial support that helps reduce their \nliving expenses while interning on Capitol Hill. C2C is \npartnered with more than 100 Congressional offices, \nbuilding the foundation for a more collaborative and \neffective government.\n\nT. HOWARD FOUNDATION DIVERSITY-TECH  \nINTERNSHIP PROGRAM \nIn December of 2021, Fox Corporation became the  \ncharter sponsor of the T. Howard Foundation’s (THF) \nDiversity-TECH (Train, Empower, Connect & Hire) \ninitiative. The program, an expansion of THF’s \nsuccessful Internship Program, offers technology \ninternships in media-related industries to diverse \nand underrepresented college students with STEM \nbackgrounds. The FOX Studio Lot will serve as the home \nof THF’s West Coast initiatives.\n\nStudent interns will be selected in February of 2023 and \nbegin the program in March. In its inaugural year, the \nfocus will be on the Data Analytics and Cybersecurity \nside of the business.\n\nFOX SPORTS UNIVERSITY \nFOX Sports University is a unique program connecting \ncollege students with FOX Sports employees and our \nLeague partners to collaborate on projects relevant to \nthe sports industry and student curriculum. \n\nFor over 14 years, FOX Sports University has been \nbringing the real world into the classroom, allowing \nstudents to bring their creative and innovative ideas to life.\n\nDuring the 2021-2022 school year, the program \npartnered with 19 prestigious universities nationwide \nengaging over 500 students. We recognize and support our colleagues  \nby promoting inclusion and diversity, offering competitive \ncompensation and benefits, affording workplace flexibility for  \nwork-life balance, providing learning and development opportunities, \nand fostering workplace civility and respect. We are committed to \nfreedom of association and the protection of human rights.\n\nINCLUSION AND DIVERSITY\n\nWe are committed to diversity from the very top. Our Board of \nDirectors requires that minority and female candidates are presented \nfor consideration with each director vacancy. We believe that the \nmore voices in the room and the more diverse the experiences \nof our colleagues, the better FOX’s internal culture and external \nprogramming are. Our diversity enables us to be more reflective of the \naudiences we reach and enhances our ability to create news, sports \nand entertainment programming that serves all viewers across the \ncountry. An inclusive and diverse workplace is not merely a strategy \nor business objective—it is fundamentally woven in the fabric of \nthe Company. This commitment begins with our approach to talent \nrecruitment across all our disciplines and extends to the way we \nnurture and advance our colleagues’ careers.\n\nThe Executive Vice President of Human Resources and the Vice \nPresident of Diversity & Inclusion monitor and oversee diversity \ninitiatives and data on an ongoing basis. Moreover, we have voluntarily \nposted on our corporate website our 2021 Employment Information \nReport (EEO-1), showing the race, ethnicity and gender of our U.S. \nemployees. For example, by the end of 2021, our first/mid-level \nofficials (EEO-1 Category 1.2) and managers were approximately \n41.7% female and 30.6% non-White. Similarly, our employees \ncategorized as professionals (EEO-1 Category 2.0) were 36.7%  \nfemale and 35.3% non-White. We are proud of our workforce and  \nour ongoing efforts to further its diversity.\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##FOX has several talent recruitment initiatives designed \nto identify, attract, hire, build and retain promising \ntalent. We have a centralized recruitment team that \nensures our job postings are written and distributed to \nappeal to candidates broadly and on an equal basis. We \nlist our job openings internally and externally because \nwe believe this is one of the best tools to reach the \nwidest and most diverse pool of candidates.\n\nWe offer paid internships to build a diverse pipeline \nof early-career talent and emerging leaders. The \nFOX Internship Program offers students an exciting \nopportunity to gain practical experience, participating \nin real-world projects and seminars on the media \nindustry, technology and professional development. This \ninternship program, which runs for 8-10 weeks three \ntimes per year, welcomed over 380 students in calendar \nyear 2021 and was listed in Vault’s 2022 “100 Best \nInternships” survey.\n\nWe also partner with the Emma Bowen Foundation, the \nT. Howard Foundation, the International Television and \nRadio Society, Sports Biz CARES and the Entertainment \nIndustry College Outreach Program to provide media \ninternships for promising students.\n\nFOX has developed and implemented a number \nof internal training programs designed to provide \noutstanding individuals with workforce skills and \nprofessional development opportunities. These \nprograms build the pipeline of our next generation of \nleaders, many of whom are from underrepresented \nbackgrounds. Examples include:\n\nFOX Ad Sales Training (FAST):  \nThis rotational program, which hired its first class in \nearly 2021, aims to attract, develop and retain early \ncareer talent. Through exposure to various functions \nwithin Ad Sales, FAST develops professional skills of \npromising individuals recruited from outside FOX. \n\nFOX Alternative Entertainment (FAE) FASTRACK:  \nThis highly selective accelerated producers’ initiative \nis designed to nurture producers with diverse \nbackgrounds and life experiences and create a pipeline \nfor new behind-the-camera talent on FAE series. \nLaunched in 2020, the program places candidates as \nassociate producers on production teams across various \nFAE-produced shows to provide valuable exposure to \nmany facets of production.\n\nFOX News Leadership Development Program:  \nThis program equips diverse, high-potential talent with \nthe tools needed to build and propel a career with FOX. \nProgram pillars are mentorship, access and networking, \nskill-building and development and exposure to the \nother FOX businesses.\n\nFOX News Media Career Launch Program:  \nInitiated in August 2021, this program strives to set  \nup early-career talent for success by providing tools  \nand resources that empower them to navigate their  \nown career journey and become well-rounded \nemployees who contribute to the long-term success  \nof FOX News Media.\n\nFOX News Media Digital Rotational Program:  \nLaunched in June 2021, this program strives to identify \nhigh potential talent from diverse backgrounds with a \npassion for the FOX News Media brand. The goal is to \nfind staff placement for the individuals who complete \nthe one-year rotational program across three key \ndepartments for four months each and have proven \nthemselves to be integral members of the FOX News \nMedia Digital team.\n\nFOX News Media High-Octane Mentoring Program:  \nUnder the mentorship of executive leadership team \nmembers, mentees who exhibit a track record of \nconsistently high performance and collaborative and \ninclusive leadership within their teams are provided \n\nwith opportunities to build their business acumen and \nleadership competencies. Launched in October 2021, \nthis program aims to engage, retain and prepare high \npotential talent for continued growth within FOX  \nNews Media.\n\nFOX News Multimedia Reporters Training Program: \nThis program places talent from diverse backgrounds \nin multimedia reporter roles across the country, where \nthey shoot, report, edit and produce their own high- \nend content across FOX News platforms. Through  \ndaily guidance and feedback from management, we \nchallenge and enable talent to continually hone their \njournalistic skill.\n\nFOX Sports Professional Development Program:  \nThis program prepares production team leaders with \nskills for the unique sports production environment, \nsuch as communication and influence in the control room \nunder short deadlines.\n\nFOX Television Stations Sales Training Program:  \nThis program was created to develop and mentor \nthe next generation of diverse and motivated sales \nprofessionals for FOX Television Stations. Trainees \nparticipate in both intensive classroom study of all \naspects of the television station advertising sales \nbusiness and shadowing of FOX Television Stations  \nsales account executives.\n\nFOX Writers Incubator Initiative:  \nThis FOX Entertainment program, which welcomed its \nfirst class in March 2022, nurtures and trains talented \nwriters with diverse voices, backgrounds and life \nexperiences. Writers work intensively on their scripts \nwith the support of established writers, executives, \ndirectors and producers across all genres (comedy, \ndrama, animation, etc.).\n\nINTRODUCTION\nABOUT FOX \nOUR APPROACH \nFISCAL YEAR 2022 HIGHLIGHTS  \nCOMMUNITY FORWARD\n\nPEOPLE FORWARD\nInclusion & Diversity\nCompensation & Benefits  \nWork-Life Balance & Workplace Flexibility \nLearning & Development \nFostering Workplace Civility & Respect\n\nSUSTAINABLY FORWARD\nPOLICY FORWARD\nDATA FORWARD\nSASB APPENDIX\n\n24\n\nFOX also collaborates with an array  \nof professional organizations that \noffer the Company access to talent \nat recruiting events and conventions. \nThese organizations include:\n\n•  ADCOLOR\n\n•  Asian American Journalists  \n\nAssociation (AAJA)\n\n•  National Association of  \nBlack Journalists (NABJ)\n\n•  National Association of  \n\nHispanic Journalists (NAHJ)\n\n•  Native American Journalists  \n\nAssociation (NAJA)\n\n•  NLGJA: The Association of  \n\nLGBTQ Journalists\n\n•  Radio Television Digital News  \n\nAssociation (RTDNA)\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##FOX also facilitates Employee Resource Groups (ERGs), \nwhich are formed around shared identity, interests or \npursuits. We support these working arrangements \nby deploying online collaboration tools, offering \ne-learning courses on effective remote work, providing \nreasonable office supplies and reimbursing business \nexpenses.\n\nThe Company also reimburses employees who work \non a fully remote basis with a monthly stipend for \nbusiness expenses (including mobile or other devices, \nInternet and electricity). opportunities \nfor all employees and applicants for employment. \nWe comply with and exceed the International Labour \nOrganization’s (ILO) conventions for eliminating \ndiscrimination in respect to employment and occupation.\n\nOur commitment to creating and maintaining an \nenvironment free of discrimination and harassment \nbegins at the highest leadership level of the Company \nand is embedded throughout our policies and practices. \nThe FOX Standards of Business Conduct and the \nPreventing Harassment, Discrimination and Retaliation \nPolicy, which are posted on our website, lay out our \nframework for addressing complaints and taking \nremedial measures as needed.\n\nOur Standards of Business Conduct expressly state that \nFOX endeavors to ensure that the workplace “is free \nof bullying and harassment, whether the harassment \nis sexual in nature, or is based on any characteristic \nprotected by applicable law.” It makes clear that it is \nour policy to “investigate promptly and thoroughly any \ncomplaint of discrimination or harassment and to take \nremedial measures if FOX determines that there has \nbeen a violation of FOX’s policy against such conduct.”\n\nWe are also committed to maintaining a workplace that \ntreats all employees with dignity and respect, and is \nfree from all forms of harassment, discrimination and \nretaliation. Our Preventing Harassment, Discrimination \nand Retaliation Policy protects individuals on the basis \nof a person’s actual or perceived race, religious creed, \ncolor, national origin, ancestry, citizenship, age, physical \ndisability, mental disability, medical condition, genetic \n\ninformation, marital status, family status, caregiver \nstatus, sex (including pregnancy status, childbirth, \nbreastfeeding, and related medical conditions), gender, \ngender identity, gender expression, sexual orientation, \nsexual and reproductive health decisions, reproductive \nhealth decision-making, hair texture or hairstyles, \nmilitary or veteran status, political affiliation, arrest or \nconviction record, union membership, unemployment \nstatus, credit history, status as a victim of domestic \nviolence, stalking or sexual offenses, or any other legally \nprotected characteristic.\n\nAny employee or applicant who believes they have \nexperienced or witnessed harassment, discrimination or \nretaliation, including as a bystander, must immediately \nreport it to a manager in the Company’s Human \nResources department or to one of several alternative \nreporting channels, including the confidential, third-\nparty managed Alertline, which allows for anonymous \nreporting of concerns. Members of management who \nlearn of harassing, discriminatory or retaliatory conduct \nfrom any source are required to report it immediately.\n\nReported concerns are investigated, and if FOX \ndetermines that a violation of this policy has occurred, \nwe take appropriate remedial action. These reports \nand investigations are evaluated by the most senior \nmembers of FOX’s management team. The Chief Legal \nand Policy Officer must approve any settlement related \nto a violation of the FOX Standards of Business Conduct \nas well as claims related to sexual harassment or other \nforms of discrimination. Further, the Audit Committee \nof the Board of Directors is informed of all matters that \nrequire the Chief Legal and Policy Officer’s approval.\n\nThe Board has also adopted a clawback policy, whereby \nthe Compensation Committee has sole discretion to \nrequire reimbursement of all or any portion of any \nperformance-based compensation or discretionary \nbonus paid to any executive for the period when the \nexecutive engaged in harassment, discrimination and/or \nretaliation, including the failure to respond to allegations \nor complaints of such behaviors. All new hires must \ncomplete training on the Preventing Harassment, \nDiscrimination and Retaliation Policy, as well as \ncompliance and business ethics, and existing employees \nmust complete the training periodically.\n\nFREEDOM OF ASSOCIATION \nFOX has always been and will continue to be \nunequivocally committed to our employees and their \nright to freely associate with any third party. Indeed, our \nPreventing Harassment, Discrimination and Retaliation \nPolicy forbids discrimination on the basis of political \naffiliation or union membership. We firmly adhere to the \nNational Labor Relations Act (NLRA). The NLRA and  \nthe subsequent Taft-Hartley Amendments protect rights \nof employees and employers in the private sector.  \nThe foundation of the NLRA includes the employees’ \nright to participate in protected, concerted activities,  \nto discuss working conditions openly and to choose to  \nbe or not be associated and/or represented by a  \nthird-party representative without fear of discrimination \nor retaliation. Across FOX Entertainment, FOX Sports, \nFOX Television Stations and the FOX Studio Lot,  \nwe are a party to approximately 75 separate collective \nbargaining agreements that cover thousands of staff  \nand freelance employees.\n\nINTRODUCTION\nABOUT FOX \nOUR APPROACH \nFISCAL YEAR 2022 HIGHLIGHTS  \nCOMMUNITY FORWARD\n\nPEOPLE FORWARD\nInclusion & Diversity\nCompensation & Benefits  \nWork-Life Balance & Workplace Flexibility \nLearning & Development \nFostering Workplace Civility & Respect\n\nSUSTAINABLY FORWARD\nPOLICY FORWARD\nDATA FORWARD\nSASB APPENDIX\n\n31\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##COMMITMENT TO DIVERSE EXPRESSION \nThe core values of our business—a free press, free \nspeech and free expression—reflect our commitment to \nour audiences’ right to know, be informed and participate \nin the marketplace of ideas. These key principles are embodied \nin FOX’s Human Rights Statement. Additionally, \nFOX supported two community planting events during Earth Month, \nbringing our total number of trees planted to 20,000.\n\nFOX Weather also teamed with One Tree Planted during Earth Month \nto replant trees in Mayfield, Kentucky, after a devastating tornado \ntore through the town in December of 2021. As stated in this policy, the responsibilities \ninclude the following:\n\n•  Issue the organization’s EHS Policy, setting the example for  \n\nFOX’s culture\n\n•  Assume overall responsibility for implementing the EHS Policy  \n\nat all FOX facilities\n\n•  Assess information provided during periodic EHS management  \n\nreviews, and direct actions to continually improve the EHS  \nmanagement program and reduce risk in the workplace\n\nThe day-to-day management of environmental issues is overseen by  \nour President of Operations and Distribution and implemented by our  \ndedicated Environmental, Health and Safety team.\n\nAdditionally, under EHS, the FOX Global Security team oversees the \nCompany’s security and emergency response efforts. The team  \nproactively monitors, reports and responds to potential and actual \nthreats to people, physical assets and property, as well as productions \nand events, using a number of tools including advanced technology, \nactive training programs, risk assessment and management processes.\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##RESOURCE EFFICIENCY AND EMISSIONS\n\nOur EHS team tracks the energy and fuel used in the course of  \nour business, develops new methods to improve energy efficiency  \nand creates campaigns to engage employees, audiences,  \nvendors and industry partners on environmental issues.  \nOngoing initiatives to reduce energy consumption and related  \ngreenhouse gas emissions include:\n\n•  Implementing Environmental and Energy Management (EEM)  \n\nsoftware to manage energy and GHG emissions across the  \nCompany’s portfolio of facilities\n\n•  Constructing new buildings to LEED certified standards\n•  Installing high-efficiency LED lights on production stages\n•  Adding occupancy/motion switches in common areas and  \n\nselected offices\n\n•  Replacing older HVAC systems with more efficient units\n•  Purchasing fuel efficient vehicles for news teams\n•  Offering and managing commuter programs, including a  \n\nQualified Transportation Expense benefit that encourages  \nemployees to commute via mass transit\n\nINTRODUCTION\nABOUT FOX \nOUR APPROACH \nFISCAL YEAR Initiatives include the EMA School Garden  \nProgram providing nationwide education for children  \non the value of organic/sustainable farming and healthy \neating.\n\nSUSTAINABLE PRODUCTION ALLIANCE \nFOX is a member of the Sustainable Production Alliance \n(SPA), a collaboration among the major studios housed \nunder the Producers Guild of America (PGA) as part  \nof the PGA Green program. The goal of the alliance is to \nfind tools and solutions to minimize the environmental \nimpact of the entertainment industry, as well as provide \nleadership in sustainability that all stakeholders in  \nthe industry can follow. Other members include Sony, \nNBCUniversal, Disney, Warner Bros. Discovery, Netflix, \nAmazon Studios, Amblin Partners, Paramount Global, \nParticipant Media and Hasbro.\n\nALBERT \nFOX assisted with the development of a voluntary  \nstudio sustainability standard in partnership with albert,  \na UK-based organization that supports the global film  \nand TV industry to reduce the environmental impacts  \nof production and to create content that supports a vision \nfor a sustainable future. The standard will allow studios \nto focus and pinpoint key areas within their facility  \nwhere they can make improvements to reduce their  \nenvironmental impact over six key areas: Climate,  \nCircularity, Nature, People, Management and Data.\n\nGREEN SPORTS ALLIANCE SUSTAINABILITY \nASSESSMENTS \nThis year, FOX collaborated with the Green Sports  \nAlliance (GSA) to better understand our impacts  \non remote productions through comprehensive  \nsustainability assessments. Our assessments took  \nplace at two NASCAR productions in Phoenix and  \nKansas City and gave insight into current impacts,  \ngaps and opportunities through material waste,  \nenergy, emissions and employee engagement.  \nAs FOX Sports continues to broadcast elite sports  \nproductions across the world, it is vital to understand \nbaseline environmental performance within its  \ncontrol of influence and develop an action plan that  \nwill increase operating efficiencies, grow brand value, \nmitigate risk and engage internal and external  \nstakeholders. We will continue to explore and engage  \nour remote productions to position our teams as a  \nleader in sports broadcasting and across the green  \nsports movement.\n\nENVIRONMENTAL EFFORTS WITH MLB GREEN \nThis MLB Season, FOX engaged with MLB Green on  \nvarious environmental initiatives at several events  \nincluding the All-Star Game, Field of Dreams,  \nPostseason Playoffs and the World Series. Efforts  \nincluded distributing reusable aluminum PATH  \nwater bottles, setting up water refill stations,  \ndonating leftover food, utilizing recycle bins and  \npurchasing offsets. We look forward to continuing  \nour relationship with MLB Green into the next MLB  \nSeason and Postseason. \n\nINTRODUCTION\nABOUT FOX \nOUR APPROACH \nFISCAL YEAR 2022 HIGHLIGHTS  \nCOMMUNITY FORWARD  \nPEOPLE FORWARD\n\nSUSTAINABLY FORWARD\nEnvironmental Employee Engagement \nEHS Program\nResource Efficiency & Emissions\nIndustry Collaboration &  \nEnvironmental Initiatives \nSupply Chain Management\n\nPOLICY FORWARD\nDATA FORWARD\nSASB APPENDIX\n\n37\n\nFORMATION OF FOX SPORTS CARBON COUNCIL \nThis year, FOX has formed an employee group  \nwithin FOX Sports known as the Carbon Council.  \nThis group meets monthly and consists of dedicated  \nemployees with an interest in sustainability. That standard is set forth in the comprehensive policies and \ncodes that govern our ethical conduct and responsible behavior.\n\n•  Standards of Business Conduct outlines our principles regarding \nfair, ethical and honest business dealings, full and fair disclosure, \nand compliance with applicable laws, and confirms the expected \nstandard of behavior governing all FOX employees and businesses. \n\n•  Statement of Corporate Governance sets forth the Company’s  \n\ncorporate governance guidelines and practices, and ensures the \nCompany is governed in a manner that serves the interests of our \nshareholders, colleagues and other stakeholders.\n\n•  Global Anti-Bribery and Anti-Corruption Policy confirms our  \ncommitment to never engage in, tolerate or condone bribery,  \ncorruption or similar conduct. This policy applies globally to every \ndirector, officer and employee of FOX and its majority-owned  \nsubsidiaries and divisions, as well as to third parties acting on  \nbehalf of FOX and its subsidiaries.\n\n•  Political Activities Policy establishes standards for employees to \n\nensure compliance with gift, lobbying and political contribution laws,  \nand any additional, more restrictive requirements required by FOX.\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##ETHICS AND COMPLIANCE PROGRAM OVERSIGHT\n\nOVERSIGHT \nThe Audit Committee of the Board of Directors has responsibility  \nfor the content and operation of FOX’s business ethics and  \ncompliance program, including anti-bribery and corruption programs \nas well as any legal or regulatory matter that could have significant \nimpact on FOX’s financial statements. The Chief Ethics and Compliance  \nOfficer reports to senior management and to the Audit Committee \nabout existing compliance programs and proposed new initiatives.  \nThe Company has adopted several operational compliance policies \nand programs, including an Anti-Bribery and Anti-Corruption Policy, \nan Insider Trading and Confidentiality Policy, a Political Activities  \nPolicy, and a Global Sanctions, Anti-Boycott and Import/Export Policy.\n\nFOX’s Chief Ethics and Compliance Officer leads the Company’s  \nethics and compliance program and assists the Board of Directors in  \nfulfilling its oversight duties concerning compliance with applicable \nlaws, regulations and accounting standards, and the dissemination  \nof true and accurate information. On behalf of senior management,  \nthe Chief Ethics and Compliance Officer ensures processes are fully \nembedded in the business.\n\nThe Chief Ethics and Compliance Officer works with liaisons in each \nbusiness unit to coordinate compliance policies and controls and  \nrelated ongoing risk assessments.\n\nDYNAMIC RISK ASSESSMENTS\n\nWe undertake various risk assessments as part of our efforts to  \nensure compliance with our Standards of Business Conduct and  \nother compliance policies. These include:\n\n•  All compliance-sensitive vendors are identified and escalated to the \nChief Ethics and Compliance Officer for risk assessment and review \nbefore being approved. We utilize both subjective assessments and \nscreening of all vendors embedded in the intake process for our \nAccounts Payable/Vendor Management system.\n\nINTRODUCTION\nABOUT FOX \nOUR APPROACH \nFISCAL YEAR 2022 HIGHLIGHTS  \nCOMMUNITY FORWARD  \nPEOPLE FORWARD\nSUSTAINABLY FORWARD\n\nPOLICY FORWARD \nOur Policies\nEthics & Compliance\nDynamic Risk Assessments\n\nDATA FORWARD\nSASB APPENDIX\n\n39\n\n•  Through periodic compliance risk assessments, FOX identifies  \n\nand assesses operations that present the greatest compliance risk \nand prioritizes resources to address those risk areas.\n\n•  Financial transactions involving onboarding of government-related  \n\nvendors must be reviewed and approved by, among others, the \nChief Ethics and Compliance Officer.\n\n•  The FOX Corporate Audit group periodically reviews the  \n\ncompleteness and reliability of this practice. Employees can approach a  \nmanager in Human Resources or an attorney in the  \nLegal Department, in any FOX business unit.\n\nThe Chief Ethics and Compliance Officer and designated \ncompliance or legal liaison in each respective business \nunit are also available to serve as additional resources.\n\nAny stakeholder (including employees, suppliers,  \ncustomers and other third parties) can also use FOX’s \nindependently managed Alertline. Alertline supports \nanonymous reporting of concerns either through a  \ndedicated, domestic/international toll-free telephone \nnumber available 24 hours a day, 365 days a year, or \nthrough a secure website.\n\nTranslation services are available through Alertline. \nReports are treated confidentially. Alertline (both online \nand telephonic) is maintained by a third-party provider.  \nThe system generates an auditable log of all concerns \nthat are received through that system. A summary of  \nthe complaint is distributed by the system to senior \nmembers of the Audit, Legal and HR teams, as well as \nthe Chief Ethics and Compliance Officer, who decide \nwhat further action may be necessary.\n\nOn a quarterly basis, the Senior Vice President of  \nCorporate Audit reports on whistleblower complaints  \nto FOX senior management and to the Audit Committee \nof the Board of Directors.\n\nThe Chief Ethics and Compliance Officer also plays a role \nin the resolution of complaints, where warranted.  \nIn addition, there may be certain circumstances when  \na colleague or anyone with an ethics or compliance  \nconcern believes that they cannot communicate that \nconcern through regular channels. In such a situation, \n\nthat person may communicate directly with the Lead \nIndependent Director of FOX’s Board, by addressing a \nletter to the attention of Lead Independent Director,  \nFox Corporation, 1211 Avenue of the Americas, New \nYork, NY 10036.\n\nINTEGRITY IN SPORTS BETTING \nFOX Sports is synonymous with the best live sports \nevents in the country. The Company also operates a \nlicensed sports-betting marketing affiliate site and has \nother relationships with and involving the licensed U.S. \nsports-betting industry. For all those reasons, ensuring \nthe integrity of sporting events and wagering, and  \navoiding even the appearance of impropriety, are critical.  \nAt all times, gaming and broadcast integrity are at the \nforefront. FOX is committed to expanding sports fans’ \nexperience responsibly and ethically.\n\nAt FOX, we never exploit our positions for personal  \ngain in gaming, broadcasting, or otherwise.  \nOur Standards of Business Conduct demonstrate our  \nfidelity to our focus on acting ethically and refraining \nfrom self-dealing.\n\n•  As one of the world’s leading sports broadcasters, \n\nFOX personnel may learn information about  \nsporting events and athletes before it becomes \nknown to the public. We do not share non-public  \ninformation except as part of our journalistic  \nresponsibilities. We never use it for personal gain.  \nFor example, members of the production team  \non FOX’s broadcast of an NFL football game might \nlearn before the game begins that one team’s starting \nquarterback suffered a serious injury while warming \nup—information not yet known to the general public. \nAny FOX personnel learning of this information would \nbe prohibited from betting on the game and would \nalso be prohibited from sharing the information with \nfriends, family members or acquaintances before it \nbecomes known to the general public. Similarly, if the \n\ninjured football player was a member of the USFL, \nthat player’s teammates would be barred from  \nsharing the information with third parties. \n\n•  FOX personnel may not wager with or through a \n\nFOX-controlled or affiliated sportsbook or marketing \naffiliate. FOX currently does not own majority interest \nin or control any sportsbook; however, FOX’s Outkick \nMedia LLC, for example, is a licensed sports-betting \nmarketing affiliate. FOX personnel may not open  \nany account or place any wager through Outkick or \nany other marketing affiliate or sportsbook in  \nwhich FOX may acquire a majority interest or control \nin the future.\n\n•  Not only are FOX employees required to refrain  \n\nfrom improperly benefiting from their position or  \naccess, they must also guard against family,  \nhousehold members and others receiving improper \nbetting advantages.\n\n•  We do not promote unlawful or unlicensed betting. \n\nFOX prohibits its personnel from endorsing,  \npromoting or otherwise advancing unlawful or  \nunlicensed sports betting or gambling.\n\n•  At FOX, we always uphold the integrity of sporting \n\nevents or sports betting that FOX broadcasts or  \npromotes. FOX’s unique position as a leading sports \nbroadcaster, coupled with its relationship to the \nsports betting industry, necessitates extra care to \navoid even the appearance of impropriety in this area. \nWe avoid taking any step that might be viewed as  \ncreating that perception and promptly report any  \nincident or event that might do so. \n\nFOX employees are encouraged to seek clarification  \non the use of non-public information from the Legal  \nDepartment, the Chief Ethics and Compliance Officer  \nand the Chief Legal and Policy Officer.\n\nINTRODUCTION\nABOUT FOX \nOUR APPROACH \nFISCAL YEAR 2022 HIGHLIGHTS  \nCOMMUNITY FORWARD  \nPEOPLE FORWARD\nSUSTAINABLY FORWARD\n\nPOLICY FORWARD \nOur Policies\nEthics & Compliance\nDynamic Risk Assessments\n\nDATA FORWARD\nSASB APPENDIX\n\n40\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##POLITICAL INVOLVEMENT \nIn 2022, FOX amended the Political Activities Policy  \nto provide for Nominating and Corporate Governance  \nCommittee oversight of the Company’s political  \nactivities and the publication of the annual  \nPolitical Activities Report, as well as to include an  \naffirmation that fees paid to industry trade organizations \nare for membership dues and not earmarked for  \nindirect grassroots lobbying. \n\nFOX’s Political Activities Policy is designed to ensure  \nthat all FOX employees, officers and directors comply \nwith all laws and regulations that apply to political  \nactivities due to employment or association with FOX. \nThe Report focuses on six areas of political activity: \n\n•  providing gifts or other items of value to public officials; \n•  lobbying lawmakers and government officials on  \n\npolicies that are important to FOX; \n\n•  making corporate or personal political contributions; \n•  running for political office; \n•  supporting the FOX Political Action Committee  \n\n(FOXPAC); and \n\n•  trade association membership. \n\nThe FOX Political Activities Report also outlines the \nCompany’s engagement efforts in six areas of corporate \npolitical activity in 2021: \n\n•  the amounts and recipients of contributions made  \n\nby the FOX Political Action Committee; \n\n•  the amounts and recipients of corporate political  \n\ncontributions to state and local candidates; \n\n•  total federal lobbying expenses; \n•  specific policy issues on which the FOX Government \n\nRelations office advocated; \n\n•  the names of executives and outside consulting firms \n\nthat performed lobbying activities for us; and \n\n•  our trade association memberships and certain \n\nnon-profit organization contributions. \n\nEDITORIAL GUIDELINES AND BROADCAST STANDARDS \nThe First Amendment and the fundamental values it  \nembodies help define who we are and what we do.  \nAs an important source of news, information, analysis \nand media, we play a leading role in the marketplace  \nof ideas. Our flagship news properties are some of the \nmost influential in history, and we respect the significant  \nresponsibility that comes with being a steward of the \npeople’s right to know. The core values of our entire \nbusiness—free press, free speech and free  \nexpression—reflect our commitment to the people’s  \nright to know, to be informed and to participate  \nin the marketplace of ideas. FOX’s Standards of  \nBusiness Conduct, Employee Handbook and  \nStandards & Practices Program Standards Manual  \nconfirm our position and expectations regarding editorial  \nindependence and broadcast standards. Employees  \nare required to read the policies and acknowledge that \nthey have done so.\n\nFOX is committed to:\n\n•  Accuracy and editorial independence: Our news  \n\norganizations carefully vet sources and check facts, \nand we maintain strict separation between revenue \nsources and our news and opinion content.\n\n•  Freedom of speech and the press: We zealously  \n\nguard and defend our journalists in their search for \nthe truth. Indeed, we believe so strongly in these core \nvalues that we have often come to the defense of our  \ncompetitors, recognizing that a free press benefits  \nall of us and requires the support of each and every \none of us.\n\n•  Protection of the newsgathering process: FOX  \n\nprotects the integrity of the entire newsgathering and \neditorial process. We safeguard the confidentiality \nof information, communications and sources that our \njournalists acquire in the course of their reporting.  \n\nWe defend against external intrusion into the editorial  \nor thought processes of our newsroom personnel, \nincluding the disclosure of drafts, edits or  \nconfidential newsroom discussions about which  \nstories merit publication.\n\n•  Journalistic independence: FOX staunchly supports \n\nthe editorial judgments of our reporters and will  \nresist the attempts of litigants, regulators or other \nthird parties to infringe on them.\n\n•  Respecting of cultural rights and diversity: Various \n\nFOX programming and advertising guidelines outline \nour expectations regarding sensitivity to and respect  \nfor ethnic, religious, sexual and other areas of social  \nconcern.\n\n•  Equal access to content and services: FOX networks \nare widely distributed (including cable, satellite and \nstreaming), ensuring that anyone can easily gain  \naccess to our content. FOX News and FOX Business \nare available in approximately 80 million U.S.  \nhouseholds, and the FOX Network covers  \napproximately 99.9% of U.S. television households.  \nTo ensure access for people with disabilities, FOX  \nprovides closed captioning, video description and \nvisual access to emergency information.\n\n•  Promoting responsible decision making by appropriate  \naudiences: We provide V-Chip ratings and advisories, \nwhere applicable, on all entertainment programming \nand promotions longer than ten seconds (excluding \nnews and live sports), allowing parents to block  \nprograms they do not want children to watch. We are \nalso beginning to provide ratings for programming \nthat appear on our recently-acquired streaming  \nservice Tubi, which also provides parental controls  \nto block programs. \n \n\nINTRODUCTION\nABOUT FOX \nOUR APPROACH \nFISCAL YEAR 2022 HIGHLIGHTS  \nCOMMUNITY FORWARD  \nPEOPLE FORWARD\nSUSTAINABLY FORWARD\n\nPOLICY FORWARD \nOur Policies\nEthics & Compliance\nDynamic Risk Assessments\n\nDATA FORWARD\nSASB APPENDIX\n\n41\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##must be truthful, appropriate, and comply with all  \nFederal Communications Commission, Federal Trade  \nCommission and legal requirements.\n\nThe FOX Network’s Advertiser Guidelines provide a \ncomprehensive set of standards covering, among other \nthings, stereotyping and other community sensibilities, \nviolence and anti-social behavior and requirements for \nproduct claims to be fully substantiated.\n\nThe Advertiser Guidelines also mandate that every  \ncommercial airing on the FOX Network must be  \nevaluated and approved in advance by FOX’s Broadcast \nStandards Department, which reserves the right, at any \ntime, to withdraw approval of a commercial spot.\n\nFOX’s Standards & Practices Program group reviews \nadvertising and on-air promotional material to confirm it \ncomplies with regulatory and network guidelines.\n\n•  Protecting intellectual property: We engage in fair  \ncompetition, protect our intellectual property and \nrespect the intellectual property and proprietary \ninformation of others. These policies describe our businesses’  \npractices concerning personal information collected through services \nsuch as websites, mobile sites and applications. For example, FOX’s \nPrivacy Policies identify the sources of personal information, the  \npurposes for using personal information (such as to operate our  \nbusinesses or provide our products and services) and the categories \nof other parties with whom that information is shared. FOX’s Privacy  \nPolicies also provide various choices for consumers to access and  \ncontrol their personal information, including the ability to access  \nand delete their personal information.\n\nFOX also notifies users of changes to its Privacy Policies, including \ninforming users that they should look at the Effective Date of the  \napplicable policy to see when it was last revised and that any changes \nwill become effective when a revised policy is posted.\n\nFOX treats personal information consistent with these stated  \npurposes, and we comply with notice requirements under applicable \nlaw and consistent with FOX’s incident response plan.\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK## \nAn independent third-party auditing firm annually  \nassesses our adherence to the NIST Framework and  \nour program maturity against industry benchmarks.  \nThe Chief Information Security Officer updates the  \nAudit Committee of the Board of Directors quarterly  \non our cybersecurity program and on progress against \nmaturity improvement areas.\n\nFOX also regularly employs internal and external  \ntechnical penetration testing and audit procedures \nagainst our environments including those systems,  \nproducts and practices collecting or storing confidential \nbusiness and personal information—including user  \ndata—in accordance with FOX’s security policies. These \ntests are routinely performed at the application,  \ninfrastructure and network level by leading third-party \nassessment firms.\n\nFOX conducts annual mandatory company-wide  \ncybersecurity compliance training, fosters awareness  \nduring Cybersecurity Awareness Month, releases \nmonthly cybersecurity training videos and conducts \nregular targeted employee training. FOX engages  \nemployees on privacy-related risk, compliance and  \ninformation protection procedures through regular  \ntraining. Built from the \nground up in Tempe, Arizona, the state-of-the-art complex provides essential technical \nfoundations for the Company’s digital streaming and content distribution capabilities. \n\nThe 125,000 square foot complex powers all of FOX’s marquee broadcast events  \nincluding the MLB World Series, NCAA football and basketball, FIFA Men\'s and FIFA \nWomen\'s World Cups, NFL season and NFC Championships, midterm elections and  \nSuper Bowl LVII. \n\nSince its inception, the FTC team has already delivered 6,000 out of 6,500 live  \nsports and entertainment events broadcast by FOX and over 200,000 media  \nassets. We partner with \ntrusted, leading non-profit organizations committed to \nimpacting the areas closest to our homes and our hearts, \nwith a particular focus on Los Angeles and  \nNew York City, where we have our largest footprint.\n\nThis Corporate Social Responsibility Report provides  \nan annual summary of our shared value approach  \nto our corporate giving, environmental, social and  \ngovernance (ESG) activities. In addition to describing  \nthe commitments and investments that we believe are  \ncritical to the long-term sustainability of our business \nand our positive impact on our communities, this report \nalso addresses and is guided by the Sustainability  \nAccounting Standards Board (SASB) criteria, found  \non page 45. We also report through programs  \nsuch as Carbon Disclosure Project (CDP), a global  \nenvironmental disclosure system, and engage  \nwith ESG research analysts, including MSCI and  \nSustainalytics, regarding our approach. \n\nThe FOX Corporate Social Responsibility Report covers \nour activities during the fiscal year ending June 30, 2022 \n(FY2022), except as otherwise noted. Calendar years \n(CY) are marked as such or written in a four-digit format. \n\n \n\nVETERANS & FIRST RESPONDERS  \nFOX, in its current form as Fox Corporation and in  \nprevious corporate formations, is a vocal and active  \nadvocate for the veteran, active-duty military and first \nresponder communities and the caregivers and service \norganizations who support them. In addition to our  \nwork in Los Angeles with U.S.VETS, our employees, our \nnetworks and our audiences consistently rally to support \nand thank members of our armed services. \n\nYOUTH & EDUCATION \nFOX supports the education and creative development of \nthe next generation of storytellers and creative leaders. \nIn bringing the depth of the creative expertise as well as \nthe resources of FOX into the classroom, we are able to \ncreate opportunities for students to explore their passion \nand define their voice. While we look to develop a passion \nfor storytelling and a curiosity about their world at large, \nwe are also aware that many students struggle to have \ntheir basic needs met to facilitate their learning. FOX is \ncommitted to filling in the gaps for those students in our \ncommunity.\n\nSERVING OUR COMMUNITY \nThe FOX Studio Lot, with its rich and storied history,  \nhas long been a vital part of the Los Angeles community. \nOver the decades, tens of thousands of writers, actors, \nengineers, directors and other FOX colleagues have left \ntheir marks creatively and through their commitment  \nto the surrounding area. We are committed to the \nwell-being of our neighbors and support the local youth, \nresidents, small businesses and community organizations \naround each of our business headquarters, including the \ncities that are home to all 18 Owned & Operated stations. \nOur legacy is one we continue to nurture and grow in and \naround the FOX Studio Lot. \n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##COMMUNITY FORWARD\n\nDATA FORWARD\n\nPEOPLE FORWARD\n\nFISCAL YEAR \n2022 \nHIGHLIGHTS\n\nINTRODUCTION\nABOUT FOX \nOUR APPROACH\n\nFISCAL YEAR 2022 HIGHLIGHTS\n\nCOMMUNITY FORWARD  \nPEOPLE FORWARD\nSUSTAINABLY FORWARD\nPOLICY FORWARD\nDATA FORWARD\nSASB APPENDIX\n\n600,000+  \nMeals Contributed \nIn collaboration with  \nFeeding America and L.A. serve through the  \nFOX Forward initiative. Over the last year, FOX’s annual giving was \nhighlighted by three $1 million gifts:\n\n•  The first gift went to the American Red Cross Southern and  \n\nMidwest Tornadoes Campaign to support those directly affected  \nby last year’s devastating storms;\n\n•  A second gift was presented to the Tunnel to Towers Foundation’s \n\n"Fallen First Responder Home Program,” which provides \nfinancial assistance to pay mortgages of the families of fallen law \nenforcement officers and firefighters who lose their lives in the line \nof duty or to 9/11-related illnesses;\xa0\n\n•  The third gift was to the American Red Cross Humanitarian Relief \nefforts in Ukraine to aid the millions of refugees displaced by the \ninvasion.\n\nAdditionally, our FOX Giving Program matches contributions (dollar \nfor dollar) made by eligible employees to verified non-profit \norganizations, up to $1,000 per person annually. Over the course of the \nfiscal year, contributions through our FOX Giving Program exceeded \n$1.5 million, attributed to employee donations and volunteer rewards, \nwith the Company’s match doubling, and in some select campaigns, \ntripling the impact of our employees’ contributions to the causes they \ncare most about. Among the over 1,000 organizations supported were: \nBlankets of Hope, Feeding America, First Responders Children’s  \nFoundation, Kids In Need Foundation, Marine Toys for Tots Foundation, \nPolice Athletic League and Together We Rise.\n\n“The FOX Giving  \nProgram enables  \nme to make an  \neven larger annual  \ncontribution  \nto the charities  \nthat matter to me.  \nI am glad that the Our annual gift supports relief efforts in response to disasters \nacross the nation, providing safe shelter, hot meals, emotional support  \nand resources to aid in recovery.\n\nThe ADGP funds the Red Cross response efforts to more than 60,000  \ndisasters of all sizes each year across the nation, helping families and  \ncommunities become better prepared and more resilient ahead of the next \ncrisis. Vital systems and supplies must be in place before disaster strikes, \nand FOX’s dedication and critical investments ensure that the tens of  \nthousands of Red Cross workers are fully ready to turn heartbreak into hope.\n\nThose struggling after a disaster turn to the Red Cross because they know \nthey will get the support they need to begin to rebuild their lives. The Red \nCross is dedicated to engaging local communities, evidenced by the fact \nthat 90% of Red Cross workers are volunteers. FOX’s participation in the \nADGP allows volunteers to be fully trained to jump into action to help those \nstruggling in their own neighborhoods.\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##•  Westwood Charter Elementary \n\nSchool, whose art instructor \nteaches oil pastels, watercolor, \ndrawing and other creative arts  \non an age-appropriate basis to  \neach grade\n\n•  Emerson Community Charter \n\nMiddle School, which launched an \nArts & Media Academy that features \nclasses on video production, \ncostume design and scriptwriting\n\n•  Van Nuys High School, which has a \nPerforming Arts Magnet program \nthat offers classes in dance, theater, \nmusic and film\n\n•  54th Street Elementary School, \nwhich works with the Why Can’t \nWe Make A Difference Foundation \nto provide students with classes \nin drama, choir and visual arts\n\n•  Crenshaw Magnet High School, \n\nwhich includes a Visual and \nPerforming Arts Pathway with \nclasses in visual arts, dance, \nmusic, digital art and media\n\n•  Canfield Elementary School, \n\nwhich offers students programs \nin visual arts, dance and music\n\nIn Action\nFOX FOR STUDENTS\n\nIn the summer of 2021, FOX debuted its “FOX For Students” program, \na broad and deep investment in local schools across Los Angeles.  \nThe program provides 12 local schools with the resources needed  \nfor activities that ignite students’ passion in the arts, creativity and \nstorytelling.\n\nIn its first year, the program helped to provide costumes and set \nsupplies for Emerson Middle School’s drama program, LCD televisions \nfor Palms Middle School’s Modern Media and Communications Magnet \nprogram and performance equipment for 54th Street Elementary \nSchool, including microphones, speakers and computers. \n\nIn addition to these arts and education opportunities, we recognize \nthe importance of daily healthy food to enable students to thrive and \nsucceed in and outside of the classroom. We recognize and support our colleagues  \nby promoting inclusion and diversity, offering competitive \ncompensation and benefits, affording workplace flexibility for  \nwork-life balance, providing learning and development opportunities, \nand fostering workplace civility and respect. We are committed to \nfreedom of association and the protection of human rights.\n\nINCLUSION AND DIVERSITY\n\nWe are committed to diversity from the very top. Our Board of \nDirectors requires that minority and female candidates are presented \nfor consideration with each director vacancy. We believe that the \nmore voices in the room and the more diverse the experiences \nof our colleagues, the better FOX’s internal culture and external \nprogramming are. Our diversity enables us to be more reflective of the \naudiences we reach and enhances our ability to create news, sports \nand entertainment programming that serves all viewers across the \ncountry. An inclusive and diverse workplace is not merely a strategy \nor business objective—it is fundamentally woven in the fabric of \nthe Company. This commitment begins with our approach to talent \nrecruitment across all our disciplines and extends to the way we \nnurture and advance our colleagues’ careers.\n\nThe Executive Vice President of Human Resources and the Vice \nPresident of Diversity & Inclusion monitor and oversee diversity \ninitiatives and data on an ongoing basis. Moreover, we have voluntarily \nposted on our corporate website our 2021 Employment Information \nReport (EEO-1), showing the race, ethnicity and gender of our U.S. \nemployees. For example, by the end of 2021, our first/mid-level \nofficials (EEO-1 Category 1.2) and managers were approximately \n41.7% female and 30.6% non-White. Similarly, our employees \ncategorized as professionals (EEO-1 Category 2.0) were 36.7%  \nfemale and 35.3% non-White. We are proud of our workforce and  \nour ongoing efforts to further its diversity.\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##FOX has several talent recruitment initiatives designed \nto identify, attract, hire, build and retain promising \ntalent. We have a centralized recruitment team that \nensures our job postings are written and distributed to \nappeal to candidates broadly and on an equal basis. We \nlist our job openings internally and externally because \nwe believe this is one of the best tools to reach the \nwidest and most diverse pool of candidates.\n\nWe offer paid internships to build a diverse pipeline \nof early-career talent and emerging leaders. The \nFOX Internship Program offers students an exciting \nopportunity to gain practical experience, participating \nin real-world projects and seminars on the media \nindustry, technology and professional development. This \ninternship program, which runs for 8-10 weeks three \ntimes per year, welcomed over 380 students in calendar \nyear 2021 and was listed in Vault’s 2022 “100 Best \nInternships” survey.\n\nWe also partner with the Emma Bowen Foundation, the \nT. Howard Foundation, the International Television and \nRadio Society, Sports Biz CARES and the Entertainment \nIndustry College Outreach Program to provide media \ninternships for promising students.\n\nFOX has developed and implemented a number \nof internal training programs designed to provide \noutstanding individuals with workforce skills and \nprofessional development opportunities. These \nprograms build the pipeline of our next generation of \nleaders, many of whom are from underrepresented \nbackgrounds. Examples include:\n\nFOX Ad Sales Training (FAST):  \nThis rotational program, which hired its first class in \nearly 2021, aims to attract, develop and retain early \ncareer talent. Through exposure to various functions \nwithin Ad Sales, FAST develops professional skills of \npromising individuals recruited from outside FOX. \n\nFOX Alternative Entertainment (FAE) FASTRACK:  \nThis highly selective accelerated producers’ initiative \nis designed to nurture producers with diverse \nbackgrounds and life experiences and create a pipeline \nfor new behind-the-camera talent on FAE series. \nLaunched in 2020, the program places candidates as \nassociate producers on production teams across various \nFAE-produced shows to provide valuable exposure to \nmany facets of production.\n\nFOX News Leadership Development Program:  \nThis program equips diverse, high-potential talent with \nthe tools needed to build and propel a career with FOX. \nProgram pillars are mentorship, access and networking, \nskill-building and development and exposure to the \nother FOX businesses.\n\nFOX News Media Career Launch Program:  \nInitiated in August 2021, this program strives to set  \nup early-career talent for success by providing tools  \nand resources that empower them to navigate their  \nown career journey and become well-rounded \nemployees who contribute to the long-term success  \nof FOX News Media.\n\nFOX News Media Digital Rotational Program:  \nLaunched in June 2021, this program strives to identify \nhigh potential talent from diverse backgrounds with a \npassion for the FOX News Media brand. The goal is to \nfind staff placement for the individuals who complete \nthe one-year rotational program across three key \ndepartments for four months each and have proven \nthemselves to be integral members of the FOX News \nMedia Digital team.\n\nFOX News Media High-Octane Mentoring Program:  \nUnder the mentorship of executive leadership team \nmembers, mentees who exhibit a track record of \nconsistently high performance and collaborative and \ninclusive leadership within their teams are provided \n\nwith opportunities to build their business acumen and \nleadership competencies. Launched in October 2021, \nthis program aims to engage, retain and prepare high \npotential talent for continued growth within FOX  \nNews Media.\n\nFOX News Multimedia Reporters Training Program: \nThis program places talent from diverse backgrounds \nin multimedia reporter roles across the country, where \nthey shoot, report, edit and produce their own high- \nend content across FOX News platforms. Through  \ndaily guidance and feedback from management, we \nchallenge and enable talent to continually hone their \njournalistic skill.\n\nFOX Sports Professional Development Program:  \nThis program prepares production team leaders with \nskills for the unique sports production environment, \nsuch as communication and influence in the control room \nunder short deadlines.\n\nFOX Television Stations Sales Training Program:  \nThis program was created to develop and mentor \nthe next generation of diverse and motivated sales \nprofessionals for FOX Television Stations. Trainees \nparticipate in both intensive classroom study of all \naspects of the television station advertising sales \nbusiness and shadowing of FOX Television Stations  \nsales account executives.\n\nFOX Writers Incubator Initiative:  \nThis FOX Entertainment program, which welcomed its \nfirst class in March 2022, nurtures and trains talented \nwriters with diverse voices, backgrounds and life \nexperiences. Writers work intensively on their scripts \nwith the support of established writers, executives, \ndirectors and producers across all genres (comedy, \ndrama, animation, etc.).\n\nINTRODUCTION\nABOUT FOX \nOUR APPROACH \nFISCAL YEAR 2022 HIGHLIGHTS  \nCOMMUNITY FORWARD\n\nPEOPLE FORWARD\nInclusion & Diversity\nCompensation & Benefits  \nWork-Life Balance & Workplace Flexibility \nLearning & Development \nFostering Workplace Civility & Respect\n\nSUSTAINABLY FORWARD\nPOLICY FORWARD\nDATA FORWARD\nSASB APPENDIX\n\n24\n\nFOX also collaborates with an array  \nof professional organizations that \noffer the Company access to talent \nat recruiting events and conventions. \nThese organizations include:\n\n•  ADCOLOR\n\n•  Asian American Journalists  \n\nAssociation (AAJA)\n\n•  National Association of  \nBlack Journalists (NABJ)\n\n•  National Association of  \n\nHispanic Journalists (NAHJ)\n\n•  Native American Journalists  \n\nAssociation (NAJA)\n\n•  NLGJA: The Association of  \n\nLGBTQ Journalists\n\n•  Radio Television Digital News  \n\nAssociation (RTDNA)\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##FOX also facilitates Employee Resource Groups (ERGs), \nwhich are formed around shared identity, interests or \npursuits. The session highlighted the history and legacy \nbehind the sacred final resting place for unidentified \nservice members and importance of honoring those  \nwho have served our nation and providing a comforting \nspace for families to remember their loved ones.\n\nPaws of War presented a virtual tour of their New York \nlocation to FOX employees, giving an inside look at their \nprogram that trains and places shelter and support dogs \nwith U.S. military veterans that suffer from the emotional \nand physical effects of war. Providing equal \npay for equal work, without regard to race, gender or \nother protected characteristics, is an imperative at FOX. \nWe link our more senior employees’ pay to corporate \nperformance through discretionary annual incentive \ncompensation awards.\n\nWe also provide a broad array of generous benefits that \nsupport the health, wellness and financial stability of \nour employees and their families. Full-time employees \nare eligible for medical insurance through a choice of \nseveral plans. Employees may enroll family members, \nincluding same- and opposite-sex domestic partners, \nin this coverage. Freelance employees who work \na minimum number of hours are also eligible for a \nmedical plan. Many employees enjoy the convenience \nof covered telemedicine visits. In addition, we provide \nvision and dental insurance, which includes coverage \nfor adult orthodontic care. Our coverage is generous, \nwith employee contributions and costs more favorable \nthan national averages, according to a 2021 Mercer LLC \nsurvey. In addition, eligible employees may participate  \nin flexible spending accounts, health savings accounts \nand qualified transportation expense accounts.  \n \nWe also provide employees with a health advocate \nservice with experts who support employees and their \neligible family members in navigating a wide range of  \n\n \n \nhealth and insurance-related issues. In addition, we have \nonsite fitness centers in our New York and Los Angeles \nworksites.\n\nTo provide additional support during the pandemic, we \npaid full-time employees’ medical insurance premiums \nfrom March 2020 through December 2021.\n\nAdditional benefits that FOX provides to full-time \nemployees include:\n\n•  paid company holidays\n•  paid floating holidays\n•  paid vacation\n•  paid sick and safe time\n•  life insurance, accidental death and dismemberment \n\ninsurance, and business travel accident insurance\n\n•  full salary replacement for up to 26 weeks of short-\n\nterm disability\n\n•  basic long-term disability insurance\n•  tuition reimbursement\n•  charitable gift matching\n•  an employee assistance program, including onsite \ncounseling in New York and Los Angeles, as well as \nsmoking cessation and weight management programs\n\n•  cybersecurity and malware protection for personal \n\ndevices\n\n•  Our 401(k) FOX Savings Plan provides employees  \n\nwith a company contribution, and it offers a company \nmatch, Roth and post-tax contribution options,  \ncatch-up contributions and a company match true-up \nfeature \n\n \n\nWORK-LIFE BALANCE  \n \nAND WORKPLACE FLEXIBILITY\n \n \nWe believe offering our employees the tools necessary \nfor a healthy work-life balance empowers them to thrive \nin our modern workforce. To that end, FOX allows eligible \nindividuals the opportunity to work on a partially remote \n(i.e., “hybrid”) or fully remote basis in appropriate \ncircumstances. We support these working arrangements \nby deploying online collaboration tools, offering \ne-learning courses on effective remote work, providing \nreasonable office supplies and reimbursing business \nexpenses.\n\nThe Company also reimburses employees who work \non a fully remote basis with a monthly stipend for \nbusiness expenses (including mobile or other devices, \nInternet and electricity). Where appropriate, we provide \ntechnology and mobile communication devices, tailored \nto employee duties. \n\nOur parental leave policy allows eligible new parents \nto bond with their children for a substantial period \nwith full pay, and our workplaces have lactation rooms \nfor our new mothers. We provide onsite subsidized \nchildcare to full-time employees at the Los Angeles \nFOX Child Care Center. In addition, we offer backup \nchild, adult and elder care benefits to help full-time \nemployees with back-to-school transitions and \ncaregiving support while managing remote work and \nvirtual learning. Our coverage includes extra backup \ncare to use during a child’s first year to assist with a \nparent’s return to work. For calendar years 2021 and \n2022, we doubled the number of days that employees \nmay use the backup care service from 20 to 40 days per \nyear, and we also allow employees to use their backup \ncare benefits for virtual tutoring.\n\nINTRODUCTION\nABOUT FOX \nOUR APPROACH \nFISCAL YEAR 2022 HIGHLIGHTS  \nCOMMUNITY FORWARD\n\nPEOPLE FORWARD\nInclusion & Diversity\nCompensation & Benefits  \nWork-Life Balance & Workplace Flexibility \nLearning & Development \nFostering Workplace Civility & Respect\n\nSUSTAINABLY FORWARD\nPOLICY FORWARD\nDATA FORWARD\nSASB APPENDIX\n\n28\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##LEARNING AND DEVELOPMENT \n\nOur learning and development programs help employees reach their \nfull potential in a rapidly changing world.
